":"Wellmaker","meanings":["North German: occupational name for someone who manufactured drums and rollers; see   Welle   2 and   Weller   3."]},{"name":"Well","meanings":["English (London): topographic name for someone who lived near a spring or stream, from Middle English <i>well(e)</i> ‘spring, stream, well’ (Old English <i>well(a)</i>).","German: from a short form of the personal names <i>Wallo</i>, <i>Walilo</i>.","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>wël</i> ‘round’."]},{"name":"Wellmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Helmut, Klaus, Volker.","German: variant of   Welle   1, with the addition of Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’, i.e. ‘man who lived by a stream’."]},{"name":"Weller","meanings":["English (Surrey, Sussex, and Kent): topographic name for someone who lived by a spring, stream, or man-made well, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>welle</i> (in southern England) and <i>wille</i> (in south western England), from Old English <i>wella</i>, <i>well(e)</i>, <i>wiella</i>, <i>wielle</i>, <i>willa</i>, <i>wyll(a)</i>, <i>wylle</i>. This type of name, a topographic term + <i>-er</i>, is particularly typical of Sussex and its neigbouring counties.","English: occupational name for someone who casts metal or who boils salt, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, a derivative with <i>-er</i> of Old English <i>wellan</i>, <i>wiellan</i> ‘to boil’. Compare 5 below.","North German: variant of   Welle  , cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":9,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":22,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":31,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":76,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel De Welle was born about 1306, in England, her father, De Welle, was 18 and her mother, de Welle, was 33. She married John Trillow. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1306–":"umbes 1306–Surnud","1306–Female":"1306–Surnud","1304–1371":"1304–1371","1330–1374":"1330–1374"